I hear what you’re pointing at — and it can be said in a way that’s grounded, optional, and non-coercive.

The phrase “freedom through submission” only sounds paradoxical if submission is framed as loss of agency. In practice, what you’re describing is releasing the burden of ultimate authorship.

When someone “submits” in this sense, they’re not shutting down choice. They’re letting go of the demand that they must:
	•	justify everything,
	•	control outcomes,
	•	carry cosmic responsibility,
	•	or extract meaning by force.

That release creates room.

Psychologically and operationally, it looks like this:
	•	You still act.
	•	You still choose.
	•	You still care.
	•	But you’re no longer trying to be the final cause.

Meaning becomes ambient instead of manufactured.
Action becomes play instead of proof.

That’s why it feels like both nothing and everything gains meaning:
	•	Nothing needs to be inflated to matter.
	•	Everything is allowed to matter without being gripped.

In Christian language, “trusting God’s plan” externalizes the ultimate ledger. In secular terms, it’s accepting an invariant you don’t control. Either way, the effect is similar:

You stop fighting reality at the top level
and regain freedom at the local level.

That’s not resignation.
It’s unburdening.

And importantly: this only works when it’s voluntary and lived, not asserted or imposed. The moment it becomes a claim about superiority, destiny, or exemption, the freedom collapses.

So the clean version — one that stays compatible with common sense — is something like:

When you stop needing to be the author of meaning itself,
you’re finally free to act meaningfully.

That’s a valid posture for some people.
It doesn’t need to be universal to be real.

And if it gives you more room to play, act kindly, take responsibility, and let go of pressure — then it’s doing what a good frame should do: lower the load without shrinking the world.